{"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Experiment No : 03**"],"metadata":{"id":"-nD2Dfj-rYyd"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Aim :**\n","Learn basics of maplotlib library and its use as visualisation tool in data science pipeline and learn about line plots and scatter plots."],"metadata":{"id":"Pob6XTZtrrI8"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Theory :**\n","\n","Matplotlib is a multi-platform data visualization library built on NumPy arrays, and designed to work with the broader SciPy stack.\n","\n","It was conceived by John Hunter in 2002, originally as a patch to IPython for enabling interactive MATLAB-style plotting via gnuplot from the IPython command line.\n","\n","One of Matplotlib’s most important features is its ability to play well with many operating systems and graphics backends. Matplotlib supports dozens of backends and output types, which means you can count on it to work regardless of which operating system you are using or which output format you wish.\n","\n","This cross-platform, everything-to-everyone approach has been one of the great strengths of Matplotlib. It has led to a large user base, which in turn has led to an active developer base and Matplotlib’s powerful tools and ubiquity within the scientific Python world.\n","\n","In recent years, however, the interface and style of Matplotlib have begun to show their age. Newer tools like ggplot and ggvis in the R language, along with web visualization toolkits based on D3js and HTML5 canvas, often make Matplotlib feel clunky and old-fashioned."],"metadata":{"id":"3PZqj5BirxdD"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Performance :**"],"metadata":{"id":"ayTXMAyzsSJA"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["\n","import matplotlib as mpl\n","import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n","mpl.__version__"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":36},"id":"aC5KMaZxsab_","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772205756523,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":38,"user":{"displayName":"","userId":""}},"outputId":"e6296a10-d161-4663-bc58-adcf48cdd70e"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["'3.10.0'"],"application/vnd.google.colaboratory.intrinsic+json":{"type":"string"}},"metadata":{},"execution_count":1}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["#setting ploting style\n","plt.style.use('classic')"],"metadata":{"id":"JwXcgQ_2sfat"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["%matplotlib inline\n","import numpy as np\n","x = np.linspace(0, 10, 1000)\n","\n","fig = plt.figure()\n","plt.plot(x, np.sin(x))\n","plt.plot(x, np.cos(x));"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":440},"id":"4qrdy4xKslME","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772205795281,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":307,"user":{"displayName":"","userId":""}},"outputId":"9f7c1915-a063-4ad6-a825-9aed57cea863"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Saving Figures to File**\n","\n","One nice feature of Matplotlib is the ability to save figures in a wide variety of formats. Saving a figure can be done using the savefig() command. For example, to save the previous figure as a PNG file, you can run this:"],"metadata":{"id":"GhFBbMChszMs"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["#Save above plot with file named my_figure.png in Current Working Directory\n","fig.savefig('my_figure.png')"],"metadata":{"id":"mj1Hs6bXs7C3"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# Cross check the folder content\n","!ls -lh my_figure.png"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"wXtU5e3LtARa","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772205904931,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":123,"user":{"displayName":"","userId":""}},"outputId":"52e58920-d378-424f-85aa-b8f9eea06c14"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["-rw-r--r-- 1 root root 45K Feb 27 15:24 my_figure.png\n"]}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# use Image package in python to check contents of png file in cwd\n","from IPython.display import Image\n","Image('my_figure.png')"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":617},"id":"bQ8JL_V3tJaC","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772205942910,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":199,"user":{"displayName":"","userId":""}},"outputId":"55cf47af-8600-479b-993e-116978c5fa2b"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"image/png":"\n","text/plain":["<IPython.core.display.Image object>"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":6}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["#checking supported file types by matplotlib\n","fig.canvas.get_supported_filetypes()"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"iWcNwCnCtY5V","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772206005780,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":15,"user":{"displayName":"","userId":""}},"outputId":"cecb0d83-7520-4149-906e-0dc58100caf9"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["{'eps': 'Encapsulated Postscript',\n"," 'jpg': 'Joint Photographic Experts Group',\n"," 'jpeg': 'Joint Photographic Experts Group',\n"," 'pdf': 'Portable Document Format',\n"," 'pgf': 'PGF code for LaTeX',\n"," 'png': 'Portable Network Graphics',\n"," 'ps': 'Postscript',\n"," 'raw': 'Raw RGBA bitmap',\n"," 'rgba': 'Raw RGBA bitmap',\n"," 'svg': 'Scalable Vector Graphics',\n"," 'svgz': 'Scalable Vector Graphics',\n"," 'tif': 'Tagged Image File Format',\n"," 'tiff': 'Tagged Image File Format',\n"," 'webp': 'WebP Image Format'}"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":7}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Matplotlib API Interfaces**\n","\n","A potentially confusing feature of Matplotlib is its dual interfaces: a convenient MATLAB-style state-based interface, and a more powerful object-oriented interface. This section we will review them breifly."],"metadata":{"id":"fN_E1866tdqH"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**MATLAB-style Interface**\n","\n","Matplotlib was originally written as a Python alternative for MATLAB users, and much of its syntax reflects that fact. The MATLAB-style tools are contained in the pyplot (plt) interface. See the example inthe code cell below"],"metadata":{"id":"fGwAWqN2tkld"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["plt.figure()  # create a plot figure\n","\n","# create the first of two panels and set current axis\n","plt.subplot(2, 1, 1) # (rows, columns, panel number)\n","plt.plot(x, np.sin(x))\n","\n","# create the second panel and set current axis\n","plt.subplot(2, 1, 2)\n","plt.plot(x, np.cos(x));"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":440},"id":"6cK_d8FatuBT","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772206093255,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":344,"user":{"displayName":"","userId":""}},"outputId":"fd6c13db-5060-4659-a28a-1e4e4a9e01a9"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 2 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["This interface is stateful: It keeps track of the \"current\" figure and axes, which are where all plt commands are applied.\n","\n","You can get a reference to these using the plt.gcf() (get current figure) and plt.gca() (get current axes) routines.\n","\n","While this stateful interface is fast and convenient for simple plots, it is easy to run into problems.\n","\n","For example, once the second panel is created, how can we go back and add something to the first? This interface does have a solution but it is not a easy solution.\n","\n","**Object-oriented interface of Matplotlib**\n","\n","The object-oriented interface can nicely handle more complicated plots, and for when you want more control over your figure.\n","\n","Rather than depending on some notion of an \"active\" figure or axes, in the object-oriented interface the plotting functions are methods of explicit Figure and Axes objects.\n","\n","To re-create the previous plot using this style of plotting, you might do the following:"],"metadata":{"id":"oaRpSUcRt2X_"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["#First create a grid of plots\n","# ax will be an array of two Axes objects\n","fig, ax = plt.subplots(2)\n","\n","# Call plot() method on the appropriate object\n","ax[0].plot(x, np.sin(x))\n","ax[1].plot(x, np.cos(x))"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":457},"id":"WW4V4jDZuAr5","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772206168773,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":250,"user":{"displayName":"","userId":""}},"outputId":"7f28b90d-191e-49c9-c97a-b4d805f4f282"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x784044c073b0>]"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":9},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 2 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["The difference is as small as switching plt.plot() to ax.plot().\n","\n","Now we start exploring different types of plots in following sections.\n","\n","**Simple Line Plots**\n","\n","Perhaps the simplest of all plots is the visualization of a single function y = f(x).\n","\n","Here we will take a first look at creating a simple plot of this type"],"metadata":{"id":"mp-lWPQ0uFPQ"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# Import all necessary libraries\n","%matplotlib inline\n","import numpy as np\n","import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n","\n","# Plotting style chosen is seaborn whitegrid\n","plt.style.use('seaborn-v0_8-whitegrid')"],"metadata":{"id":"F-2iWgP7vupK"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# creating objects of figure and axes.\n","fig = plt.figure()\n","ax = plt.axes()"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":439},"id":"AulNBpufvZD0","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772206625273,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":145,"user":{"displayName":"","userId":""}},"outputId":"db98293a-e961-4e5c-9b24-e74b2245f12f"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["In Matplotlib, the figure (an instance of the class plt.Figure) can be thought of as a single container that contains all the objects representing axes, graphics, text, and labels.\n","\n","The axes (an instance of the class plt.Axes) is what we see above: a bounding box with ticks and labels, which will eventually contain the plot elements that make up our visualization.\n","\n","Once we have created an axes, we can use the ax.plot function to plot some data"],"metadata":{"id":"ptjtrmZrEuet"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# Import necessary libraries\n","import numpy as np\n","import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n","\n","# We will plot a sine curve using ax.plot function\n","fig = plt.figure()\n","ax = plt.axes()\n","\n","x = np.linspace(0, 10, 1000)\n","ax.plot(x, np.sin(x))\n","\n","plt.show()"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":430},"id":"gmzI7Q_DFlxv","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772212350041,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":306,"user":{"displayName":"","userId":""}},"outputId":"7ad8fea9-bb8d-4191-b3ab-9fdc1e6effd6"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["\n","The word line in line plot refers to the function we want to plot. Multiple functions can be plot on same plot like shown below"],"metadata":{"id":"VfnR1SDJFrPB"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["plt.plot(x, np.sin(x))   #shown in blue\n","plt.plot(x, np.sin(2*x)) #Shown in green\n","plt.plot(x,(x**(1/2))/2) #Shown in red"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":447},"id":"j5sl6TuhFxS8","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772212397827,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":248,"user":{"displayName":"","userId":""}},"outputId":"bde1b31e-d2a2-4124-ca62-befdec9b0efe"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x794a28523d40>]"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":6},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Adjusting the Plot:Line Colors and Styles**\n","\n","The first adjustment you might wish to make to a plot is to control the line colors and styles. The plt.plot() function takes additional arguments that can be used to specify these. To adjust the color, you can use the color keyword, which accepts a string argument representing virtually any imaginable color. The color can be specified in a variety of ways"],"metadata":{"id":"D8NTRNIFGPLd"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["plt.plot(x, np.sin(x - 0), color='blue')        # specify color by name\n","plt.plot(x, np.sin(x - 1), color='g')           # short color code (rgbcmyk)\n","plt.plot(x, np.sin(x - 2), color='0.75')        # Grayscale between 0 and 1\n","plt.plot(x, np.sin(x - 3), color='#FFDD44')     # Hex code (RRGGBB from 00 to FF)\n","plt.plot(x, np.sin(x - 4), color=(1.0,0.2,0.3)) # RGB tuple, values 0 to 1\n","plt.plot(x, np.sin(x - 5), color='chartreuse'); # all HTML color names supported"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":430},"id":"fVZcl_KfGlKi","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772212609952,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":645,"user":{"displayName":"","userId":""}},"outputId":"ce3959a9-8556-47f1-ecd5-62675f58ceb0"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["plt.plot(x, x + 0, linestyle='solid')\n","plt.plot(x, x + 1, linestyle='dashed')\n","plt.plot(x, x + 2, linestyle='dashdot')\n","plt.plot(x, x + 3, linestyle='dotted');\n","\n","# For short, you can use the following codes:\n","plt.plot(x, x + 4, linestyle='-')  # solid\n","plt.plot(x, x + 5, linestyle='--') # dashed\n","plt.plot(x, x + 6, linestyle='-.') # dashdot\n","plt.plot(x, x + 7, linestyle=':');  # dotted"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":430},"id":"eg-kgVMLGqGz","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772212632706,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":279,"user":{"displayName":"","userId":""}},"outputId":"2cb74736-e1e9-4487-9ef4-0118867dafe2"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Adjusting the Plot: Axes Limits**\n","\n","Matplotlib does a decent job of choosing default axes limits for your plot, but sometimes it's nice to have finer control. The most basic way to adjust axis limits is to use the plt.xlim() and plt.ylim() methods:"],"metadata":{"id":"jO7pU5AYGxN_"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["plt.plot(x, np.sin(x))\n","\n","plt.xlim(-1, 11)\n","plt.ylim(-1.5, 1.5);"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":435},"id":"O5zCWa3UG3cu","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772212684712,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":147,"user":{"displayName":"","userId":""}},"outputId":"bc16b2ef-7ea6-4574-cb20-4c7927973514"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# Reverse the Axis Limit\n","plt.plot(x, np.sin(x))\n","\n","plt.xlim(10, 0)\n","plt.ylim(1.2, -1.2);"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":430},"id":"20B30ls6G7Q5","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772212699886,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":156,"user":{"displayName":"","userId":""}},"outputId":"c4a2ca17-2485-4cfd-9622-5a5ff7bf5055"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["plt.plot(x, np.sin(x))\n","plt.axis([-1, 11, -1.5, 1.5]);"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":435},"id":"xLwU5hnrHKIS","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772212764922,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":140,"user":{"displayName":"","userId":""}},"outputId":"316b06e6-4794-41b5-bfb1-8d7e011768de"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Labeling Plots**\n","\n","As the last piece of this section, we'll briefly look at the labeling of plots: titles, axis labels, and simple legends.\n","\n","Titles and axis labels are the simplest such labels—there are methods that can be used to quickly set them:"],"metadata":{"id":"7NGRYrwoHSq5"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["plt.plot(x, np.sin(x))\n","plt.title(\"A Sine Curve\")\n","plt.xlabel(\"x\")\n","plt.ylabel(\"sin(x)\");"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":472},"id":"UejOPizFHfbq","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772212848030,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":266,"user":{"displayName":"","userId":""}},"outputId":"f12dd9da-9264-46b0-c399-0701281745d4"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["When multiple lines are being shown within a single axes, it can be useful to create a plot legend that labels each line type.\n","\n","Again, Matplotlib has a built-in way of quickly creating such a legend. It is done via the (you guessed it) plt.legend() method.\n","\n","Though there are several valid ways of using this, I find it easiest to specify the label of each line using the label keyword of the plot function:"],"metadata":{"id":"Ftr6u652HkVQ"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["plt.plot(x, np.sin(x), '-g', label='sin(x)')\n","plt.plot(x, np.cos(x), ':b', label='cos(x)')\n","plt.axis('equal')\n","\n","plt.legend();"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":431},"id":"kQnl-BPhHnvI","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772212882357,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":197,"user":{"displayName":"","userId":""}},"outputId":"f9c8c71a-87b5-494b-a065-b9b768bf9b4d"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["In the object-oriented interface to plotting, rather than calling these functions individually, it is often more convenient to use the ax.set() method to set all these properties at once:"],"metadata":{"id":"fcbQsvdlHx6F"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["ax = plt.axes()\n","ax.plot(x, np.sin(x))\n","ax.set(xlim=(0, 10), ylim=(-2, 2),\n","       xlabel='x', ylabel='sin(x)',\n","       title='A Simple Plot');"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":472},"id":"_zrBGwLtH1mt","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772212941168,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":109,"user":{"displayName":"","userId":""}},"outputId":"ecdde263-4d58-40b9-f70d-dcc711163986"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Simple Scatter Plots**\n","\n","Another commonly used plot type is the simple scatter plot, a close cousin of the line plot. Instead of points being joined by line segments, here the points are represented individually with a dot, circle, or other shape"],"metadata":{"id":"4eFIIos9H-Fe"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Scatter Plots with plt.scatter\n","A second, more powerful method of creating scatter plots is the plt.scatter function, which can be used very similarly to the plt.plot function:"],"metadata":{"id":"29DYQUVUIeW-"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["rng = np.random.RandomState(0)\n","for marker in ['o', '.', ',', 'x', '+', 'v', '^', '<', '>', 's', 'd']:\n","    plt.plot(rng.rand(5), rng.rand(5), marker,\n","             label=\"marker='{0}'\".format(marker))\n","plt.legend(numpoints=1)\n","plt.xlim(0, 1.8);"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":431},"id":"T_XVMDXGILE_","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772213027090,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":329,"user":{"displayName":"","userId":""}},"outputId":"818dfa81-8b61-40de-c612-ddd199bcb5cb"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Scatter Plots with plt.scatter**\n","\n","A second, more powerful method of creating scatter plots is the plt.scatter function, which can be used very similarly to the plt.plot function:"],"metadata":{"id":"FpJNGdhNIf8m"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["import numpy as np\n","import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n","\n","# Create data\n","x = np.linspace(0, 10, 100)\n","y = np.sin(x)\n","\n","# Scatter plot\n","plt.scatter(x, y, marker='o')\n","\n","plt.show()"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":430},"id":"FY0hLLB8InWd","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772213215256,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":149,"user":{"displayName":"","userId":""}},"outputId":"6520b544-b31b-4903-d6f6-d710316e6532"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# Consider this code for scatter plot\n","\n","rng = np.random.RandomState(0)\n","x = rng.randn(100)\n","y = rng.randn(100)\n","colors = rng.rand(100)\n","sizes = 1000 * rng.rand(100)\n","\n","plt.scatter(x, y, c=colors, s=sizes, alpha=0.3,\n","            cmap='viridis')\n","plt.colorbar();  # show color scale"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":430},"id":"J4otplegIsZH","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1772213164130,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":586,"user":{"displayName":"","userId":""}},"outputId":"b64271ba-f265-4050-9f34-d858a47275a1"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 2 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Question Answer Section**"],"metadata":{"id":"uwzCgh6WJBy6"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**1.List any 2 python APIs that are used for Plotting Graphs.**"],"metadata":{"id":"c56NwSqhJMPL"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":[" two Python APIs commonly used for plotting graphs are matplotlib.pyplot and matplotlib.axes"],"metadata":{"id":"c8mf2RZYJhwP"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**2.Name 2 important machnisms used for accesssing Matplotlib API.**"],"metadata":{"id":"PJbeMzXyJooU"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["The notebook describes two important mechanisms for accessing the Matplotlib API:\n","\n","1.MATLAB-style Interface: This is a state-based interface, typically accessed through matplotlib.pyplot (imported as plt). It keeps track of the 'current' figure and axes.\n","2.Object-oriented Interface: This interface provides more control by working directly with explicit Figure and Axes objects."],"metadata":{"id":"TQKfWED8JpSq"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**3.Create a collection of 100 random normal numbers with parameter mean 30, sd 4 store it in object summer_temp**"],"metadata":{"id":"njNTxCREKG0v"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["import numpy as np\n","\n","# Create a collection of 100 random normal numbers with mean 30 and standard deviation 4\n","summer_temp = np.random.normal(loc=30, scale=4, 